= Foreword <ch-foreword>

When I found out I was pregnant, I did what most women do: I panicked a little, cried a lot (happy tears), and then immediately started googling everything.

That lasted about forty-eight hours before I wanted to throw my phone into the ocean.

Everyone had advice. My mom told me what her doctor said in 1987. My best friend swore by her birth center experience. The internet told me I was going to die if I didn't get an epidural, and also that I was going to die if I did. The hospital's childbirth class was four hours of PowerPoint slides that somehow managed to cover nothing useful. Every book I picked up had an angle — either so crunchy it made me feel guilty for considering a hospital, or so clinical it read like a liability waiver.

I'm a lawyer. I'm trained to research and argue both sides. I still felt completely lost.

And honestly? I didn't want to deal with it. I knew the baby was coming, obviously. But thinking about the actual _birth_ — the process, the decisions, the what-ifs — that was something I kept putting off. I ate well, went to my appointments, handled the pregnancy stuff. The labor and delivery part? I figured we'd cross that bridge when we got there.

My husband had other plans.

He started looking into things early on — reading, asking questions, bringing me information he'd found. I'd half-listen while trying not to think about the fact that a human being was eventually going to exit my body. But the things he was finding were hard to ignore — information I'd never heard from any of our providers.

He wanted us to take a Bradley Method course together. I was not enthusiastic. Eight weeks of classes, while pregnant, when I was already exhausted — it felt like a lot. I went because he asked, and I'm grateful I did. That course changed everything for both of us. It taught us how birth actually works, what our bodies are designed to do, and how much we didn't know. Looking back, we may have started the course a little early in the pregnancy, but the extra preparation time turned out to be a gift.

After the course, things got serious. We started creating our birth plan and realized how many decisions were in front of us that we hadn't thought about. That sent us down a much deeper path — reading books, researching online, reading studies, talking to our providers. He'd bring me what he found, we'd talk it through, and we'd make decisions together. As a lawyer, I pushed back, asked hard questions, and poked holes in his conclusions. We didn't agree on everything right away. But we worked through every decision as a team — and by the time I went into labor, we understood our options and knew what we wanted.

There are a lot of great books out there on pregnancy and birth, and some of them cover individual topics in more depth than this one does. But we never found anything this consolidated — one resource with the goal of laying out the pros and cons for every major decision, equipping you to make informed choices in one place. We were always comparing different books, articles, and studies to piece together what we needed. We wanted something that did that work for you.

That's what this book is.

