We chose an unmedicated hospital birth, and that's what we got. Hardest thing I've ever done. I would do it again without hesitation.

I don't believe I could have done it without my husband. He wasn't watching from the sidelines — he was with me through the whole thing, supporting me through every contraction, communicating with our nurses, advocating for our plan when I couldn't speak for myself. We had talked through every decision before the contractions started. We'd written a birth plan. We'd brought questions to every appointment. When a nurse or doctor suggested something, it wasn't the first time we were hearing about it. We already knew the pros, the cons, and what we wanted.

The goal was always simple: healthy baby, healthy mom. We got both. And the most wonderful, precious baby we could have imagined. That outcome wasn't an accident. It was the result of months of preparation, done together. Instead of going with the flow and letting it all happen _to_ us, we were active participants in every part of the process. Informed consent meant something to us because we'd done the work to be informed. Whatever kind of birth you're planning, that preparation matters.

